                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d489">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/1–1049</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by Major General Patrick J. Hurley</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Yenan</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-11-08">8 November,
                            1944</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Theodore White, correspondent for <hi rend="italic">Time</hi> and <hi
                        rend="italic">Life</hi>, told me that he had just talked to Chairman Mao and
                    Mao had told him that there <pb facs="0688" n="674" xml:id="pg_674"/> was not
                    any possible chance of an agreement between him and Chiang Kai-shek. White told
                    me many of the reasons why Mao should not agree with the National Government.
                    White’s whole conversation was definitely against the mission with which I am
                    charged.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
